rabzon, Tyrkiet","England":"England","Rushton, Northamptonshire, England":"Rushton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England"},"nl":{"1480–18 August 1562":"1480–18 augustus 1562","1483–1582":"1483–1582","1515–1557":"1515–1557","1480–1562":"1480–1562","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","Abt. 1515":"circa 1515","1562":"1562","1582":"1582","1483":"1483"," November 1557":"november 1557","18 August 1562":"18 augustus 1562","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Of, Cople, Bedforshire, England":"Of, Trabzon, Turkije","England":"England","Rushton, Northamptonshire, England":"Rushton, Northamptonshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England"},"en":{"1480–18 August 1562":"1480–18 August 1562","1483–1582":"1483–1582","1515–1557":"1515–1557","1480–1562":"1480–1562","1558":"1558","1557":"1557","Abt. 1515":"about 1515","1562":"1562","1582":"1582","1483":"1483"," November 1557":"November 1557","18 August 1562":"18 August 1562","1480":"1480","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","Of, Cople, Bedforshire, England":"Of, Trabzon, Türkiye","England":"England","Rushton, Northamptonshire, England":"Rushton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Bedford, Bedfordshire, England":"Bedford, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mordaunt,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>mordant</i> ‘biting, sarcastic’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Baron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, English, Dutch, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and Croatian; Breton (also <b>Le Baron</b>): from Old French <i>barun</i>, <i>baron</i>, Middle English <i>barun</i>, <i>baroun</i>, Middle Dutch <i>baroen</i>, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and dialectal Croatian <i>baron</i> ‘baron’ (i.e. a nobleman ranking below an earl and above a knight), a title of nobility which was in England also awarded to certain freemen of the cities of London and York and of the Cinque Ports. As a surname it is unlikely to be a status name denoting a person of rank. Generally, it referred to service in a baronial household or was acquired as a nickname by a peasant who had ideas above his station or applied to a man showing characteristics of a nobleman. See also 3 and 4 below, compare   Barron   and   Lebaron  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Baron, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lebaron  .","German: status name for a freeman or baron, from <i>barūn</i> ‘imperial or church official’, a loanword in Middle High German from Old French (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Barron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Francisco, Carlos, Miguel, Raul, Pedro, Ruben, Alfredo, Luis.","Scottish: status name from Scots <i>baron</i>, which in the Highlands denoted a small proprietary landholder. In Angus it alluded specifically to a tenant of one of the small baronies attached to the Abbey of Coupar Angus. The surname was taken by Scottish migrants to Ulster. Compare   Baron  .","Scottish: shortened form of <b>McBarron</b>, from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bharain</b> ‘son of the baron’. See   Baron   and 1 above."]},{"name":"Boron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Krystyna, Edyta, Leszek, Mieczyslaw, Mieczyslawa, Wladyslaw.","Polish (<b>Boroń</b>): from a pet form of the personal names <i>Borzysław</i> or <i>Borzymir</i>, formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic <i>boriti se</i>).","French: habitational name from a place so called in Franche-Comté."]},{"name":"Baro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Manuel, Ana, Angel, Carlos, Cesar, Fernando, Jesus, Jose, Orlando, Ramon, Rosalia.  Italian Guido, Angelo, Carmelo, Federico, Lucio.","Catalan (<b>Baró</b>): status name from <i>baró</i> ‘free man, baron’ (see   Baron   1), or a habitational name from a place so named.","Hungarian (<b>Báró</b>): status name from <i>báró</i> ‘baron’. In the form <b>Baró</b>, it could be from a pet form of the personal names <i>Barabás</i> (see   Barabas  ) or <i>Bertalan</i>."]},{"name":"Barona","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of <b>Barón</b> ‘baron’ (see   Baron  ), applied as a nickname or as an occupational name for a member of the household of a baroness.","Italian: probably from the feminine form of   Barone  . The name is concentrated in Sondrio province (Lombardy)."]},{"name":"Barren","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Baron   or   Barran  ."]}]},{"name":"Mordaunt","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>mordant</i> ‘biting, sarcastic’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Korean Kyong, Kyong Suk, Young, Chae, Chi Young, Hang, Kil, Rin, Sang Hun, Chang, Chong, Insoo, Kum, Sun Young, Yom, Young Hwan.  Cambodian Kiwan, Oeurn, Phoeun, Pich, Saroeuth, Seung, Sophath, Sophea, Yoeun, Phan, Son.  Indian Shanti, Harendra.","Indian (Uttar Pradesh): Brahmin name, from Sanskrit <i>om</i>, the Hindu sacred and mystic syllable uttered at the beginning of prayers.","Cambodian: written ឱម, corresponding to the exclamation of solemn affirmation, of Sanskrit origin (see 1 above), chanted by Buddhist monks."],"variants":[{"name":"Oum","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Southeast Asian Heang, Hye, Kam, Kan, Kheng, Khin, Kun, Sang, Sok, Phong, Yom, Yoo, Youn, Cuong, Phal, Samnang, Tin.  Cambodian Sokha, Chheang, Choeun, Moeun, Roeun, Sambath, Samoeun, Savuth, Soeun, Sopheap.","Cambodian: written អ៊ុំ, from a Khmer word denoting an elder sibling of one's parent (i.e. ‘uncle’ or ‘aunt’). Compare   Om   3 and   Um   2."]}]},{"name":"Turvey","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire, Bedfordshire and Buckinghamshire): habitational name from Turvey, a place in Bedfordshire named from Old English <i>turf</i> ‘turf’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’. This name may have become confused with   Turville  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Turville","meanings":["English (Surrey and Hampshire; of Norman origin):","habitational name from Tourville‐la‐Campagne (Eure, France). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thórr</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ (from Latin <i>villa</i>).","occasionally a shortened form of   Turberville  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was